Now I will give a quick look to the dataset visually

In [159]:
sns.pairplot(data, corner=True, diag_kind='kde')
Out[159]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.PairGrid at 0x7f475e1bab38>

We can see thet that the 'Legendary' and the 'Generation' variables can be consider as categorical variables, since they clearly divide the data set in different categories.

Being the 'total' variable the sum of the others combact stats (HitPoints, Attack, Defense, SpecialAttack, SpecialDefense, Speed) it's noticeable (and predictable) that to higher values of the total correspond higher values of the single stats. As a matter of fact all the scatter plots that show this relationship have a behaviour which can be almost defined as linear.

It's also possilbe to notice tha attack and defense seem to have a relantionship tending to a lienear behaviour as well. Which is interesting since in some other games the player has to trade between attack or defense. This doesn't seem to be the case in Pokemon. It may be deducted that attack and defense develop evenly when pokemon evolve, so the simil linear behaviour of this relantionship may be caused by the lower level pokemon being in the bottom left and the strongest one in the top right.

Out[38]:
Text(0, 0.5, 'Cumulative Explained Variance')

From the explained variance values we can see how the Principal component accounts for 53% of the data. The second bigger component holds 15.6% of the data. The 4 compenents together hold 90% of the information. Since the rule of thumb is to preserve around 80% of the variance, we can say that reduced number of data with 4 components is a good choice.

1.4 Perform a cluster analysis (KMeans) on all numerical variables (scaled & before PCA). Pick a realistic number of clusters (up to you where the large clusters remain mostly stable).¶

In [52]:
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans

In order to decide which claster is better, I use the elbow method

In [53]:
wcss = []
for i in range(1,21):
  kmeans_sc = KMeans(n_clusters = i, init = 'k-means++')
  kmeans_sc.fit(scaled_data)
  wcss.append(kmeans_sc.inertia_)
In [54]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10,8))
plt.plot( range(1,21), wcss, marker= 'o', linestyle = '--')
plt.title('K-Means with scaled data')
plt.xlabel('Number of Clusters')
plt.ylabel('WCSS (inertia)')
Out[54]:
Text(0, 0.5, 'WCSS (inertia)')

From this graph, it's possible to determine the optimal number of clusters. According to the Elbow-method I see that the part of the the WCSS graph that is steeply declining (the elbow) is mostly between the first and second cluster marks. There is a lower, but still noticeable, decline between the second and the third. So I decide to take 3 clusters.

In [55]:
clusterer = KMeans(n_clusters=3)
data_scaled_kmeans = clusterer.fit(scaled_data) 
print(data_scaled_kmeans.inertia_)

3037.12883190608

It's possible to see that the inertia value we have after setting the number of cluster =5 is the same we have in the graph above
